[[Image:ReshevskyChild.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Eleven-year-old [[Samuel Reshevsky|Sammy Reshevsky]], New York 1922]] A '''chess prodigy''' is a child who can beat experienced adult players, and even Masters, at [[chess]]. Expectations can be high for chess prodigies. While some become [[World Chess Championship|World Champions]], others show little or no progress in adulthood.
==Early chess prodigies==
Early chess prodigies were [[Paul Morphy]] (1837–1884) and [[José Raúl Capablanca]] (1888–1942), both of whom won matches against strong adult opponents at the age of 12, and [[Samuel Reshevsky]] (1911–1992), who was giving [[simultaneous exhibition]]s at the age of six.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chessbase.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=2858|title=Chess prodigies and mini-grandmasters|date=10 January 2006|publisher=|accessdate=8 August 2017}}</ref> Morphy went on to be unofficial World Champion (before the official title existed), Capablanca became the third World Champion, and Reshevsky—while never attaining the title—was amongst the top few players in the world for many decades.
==List of youngest grandmasters==<!-- This section is linked from [[Grandmaster (chess)]] -->
One measure of chess prodigies (since 1950, when the title was introduced) is the age at which they gain the [[Grandmaster (chess)|Grandmaster]] title. Below are players who have held the record for youngest grandmaster. The record has been held by [[Sergey Karjakin]] (then Ukraine) since 2002. The age listed is the age at which they [[Norm (chess)#Grandmaster norm|qualified for the title]]. This is not equal to the age at which they officially became Grandmasters, because GM titles can only be awarded at [[FIDE]] congresses.
Note: all players are listed by their nationality at the time of gaining the title, not their current or later nationality.
