'''William Anthony Gamson''' (born January 27, 1934) is a professor of [[Sociology]] at [[Boston College]], where he is also the co-director of [[Boston College Media Research and Action Project|the Media Research and Action Project (MRAP)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.bc.edu/~gamson/Homepage(Frames).html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629185042/https://www2.bc.edu/~gamson/Homepage%28Frames%29.html |archivedate=2011-06-29 |title=William Gamson's Homepage |accessdate=2012-12-13 |publisher=[[Boston College]]}}</ref> He is the author of numerous books and articles on [[political discourse]], the [[mass-media]] and [[social movements]] from as early as the 1960s. His works include ''The Strategy of Social Protest'',<ref>''The Strategy of Social Protest'' {{ISBN|0-534-12078-4}}</ref> ''WHAT'S NEWS'' (1984),<ref>''WHAT'S NEWS'' (1984) {{ISBN|0-02-911110-2}}</ref> and ''Talking Politics'' (2002),<ref>''Talking Politics'' (2002) {{ISBN|0-521-43679-6}}</ref> as well as numerous editions of ''[[Simulated Society|SimSoc]]''.<ref>''[[SimSoc]]'' 5th edition (2000) {{ISBN|0-684-87140-8}}</ref>
Gamson, who received his Ph.D. from the [[University of Michigan]] in 1959, was the 85th [[List of American Sociological Association presidents|president]] of the [[American Sociological Association]] in 1994.<ref>[http://www.asanet.org/about/presidents/William_Gamson.cfm "Presidents: William A. Gamson"]. [[American Sociological Association]]. Retrieved 2012-12-13.</ref> He is also a [[List of Guggenheim Fellowships awarded in 1978|1978 recipient of a Guggenheim Fellowship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gf.org/78fellow.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516060355/http://www.gf.org/78fellow.html |archivedate=2008-05-16 |title=1978 Foundation Program Areas |publisher=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation |accessdate=2012-12-13}}</ref> In 1962, he won the [[AAAS Prize for Behavioral Science Research]].<ref>[http://archives.aaas.org/awards.php?a_id=24 History & Archives: AAAS Prize for Behavioral Science Research]</ref>
Gamson was instrumental in the creation of [[fantasy baseball]] and [[fantasy sports]]. He created one of the first fantasy baseball leagues in Boston in 1960, the "Baseball Seminar," where colleagues would form rosters that earned points on the players' final standings in batting average, [[Run batted in|RBI]], [[Earned run average|ERA]] and wins.<ref name="The Numbers Game p. 175">[[Alan Schwarz]]: ''The Numbers Game : Baseball's Lifelong Fascination with Statistics'' [[Thomas Dunne Books]] p. 175, {{ISBN|0-312-32222-4}}</ref> Gamson later brought the idea with him to the [[University of Michigan]] where some professors played the game. One professor playing the game was Bob Sklar, who taught an American Studies seminar which included [[Daniel Okrent]], who learned of the game his professor played. Okrent would later write a book that was the key catalyst for the modern [[fantasy sports]] industry.<ref name="The Numbers Game p. 175"/><ref>{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Hilt |coauthors= |title=Fantasy baseball league owners still bonding in their 32nd season |date=2007-06-26 |publisher= |url=http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/sports/local/story/7487701p-7382875c.html |work=Press of Atlantic City |pages= |accessdate=2007-07-17 |language= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704103821/http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/sports/local/story/7487701p-7382875c.html |archivedate=2007-07-04 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
== Gamson's Law == ''Gamson's Law of Proportionality'' or simply ''Gamson's Law'' was suggested by Eric C. Browne and Mark N. Franklin in 1971.<ref>{{JSTOR|1958776}}</ref> They stated that there is proportionality between the numerical representation of each political force in a government and their number of seats in the parliament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Party Size and Portfolio Payoffs. A Study of the Mechanism Underlying Gamson’s Law of Proportionality|url=http://ecpr.eu/Filestore/PaperProposal/8a35eb8c-6cc6-4367-8ce1-10cff324664a.pdf}}</ref> It was based on the idea that each actor in government expects a payoff proportional to the weight that it contributes to the coalition, that had been proposed in the paper ''A theory of coalition formation'', published in 1961 by William Gamson.<ref>{{JSTOR|2090664}}</ref>
